{"key":"processedPost-10782419","value":{"id":10782419,"first":10781475,"last":10792612,"when":1249181210,"utime":"08/02/09 05:46 AM","content":"84F is too hot to colonize mycelium.&nbsp; The old advice of 86F was incorrect and actually slows down colonization and increases rate of contamination.&nbsp; Don't let the ambient temp go over 80.<br /><br />You can colonize your substrates on an open shelf at normal room temperature.&nbsp; Spawn your grains into the manure, cover with foil, and set them on a bookshelf for ten days to two weeks.&nbsp; When fully colonized, let them set for an additional few days to a week.&nbsp; I like to wait a week, because I've found eventual flush and finished product weight is better.<br /><br />Temp drop is not a pinning trigger with cubes.&nbsp; You can colonize and fruit at the same temp.&nbsp; When fruiting time comes, you want lots of fresh air and 95% or better humidity.&nbsp; If you can do that with perlite, fine.&nbsp; If you use a humidifier, put it on a timer so it doesn't saturate your substrates.<br /><br />Evaporation of moisture from the substrate is a major pinning trigger, so that's why you want a lot of fresh air.&nbsp; Mist a few times daily as required to replace the moisture that is lost.<br /><br />Don't use incandescent lamps.&nbsp; Use fluorescent, and look for 'natural daylight' or 6500K on the label.&nbsp; A bright window also works well.<br />RR","title":"Re: only cow compost, no casing."}}